# Testing policy

Full strategy: `.docs/TESTING_STRATEGY.md`. Repo pitfalls: `.docs/prompting/DEVELOPMENT_GUIDELINES.md` §1.

## Default: requirements, happy path

Tests should codify **what the system must do**, not how it is implemented today.

- Prefer one clear happy-path test per behavior over many brittle assertions
- Test user-visible outcomes and public contracts (actions, API shapes, UI states)
- Do **not** add tests whose only purpose is coverage padding or line-count

## When to add depth

Add edge cases, failure modes, security tests, or regression tests **only when**:

- A bug escaped once (regression test with a one-line comment referencing the failure)
- Security or abuse is in scope (auth, input validation, rate limits, honeypots)
- The happy path hides a risky branch (e.g. stored-without-email vs total failure)
- CI would otherwise give no useful signal on regressions

Skip depth when the case is impossible, trivially typed away, or third-party library behavior.

## Maintenance cost

If a feature change forces widespread test rewrites, tests were probably too specific. Refactor toward behavior-level assertions.

## Mocks

- Mock external services (Directus, SMTP), not your own pure utilities
- Never use Proxies on frozen `lib/config` objects — use getters (see DEVELOPMENT_GUIDELINES)
